%slide20-----------------------------------------
\subsubsection{Soil food web typologies may provide the theoretical as well as the applied basis for agricultural-ecological mutualism ...}
\textit{\underline{If} it is the energetic and biochemical transformations brokered by rhizospheric fungal/bacterial/protozoa assemblages that are primarily responsible for nutrient cycling \underline{and} rhizospheric fungal/bacterial/protozoa assemblages are soil food webs fueled by the root exudates of living plants, \underline{then} different natural successional stages have unique soil food webs \underline{and} outcomes of interactions in the rhizosphere ultimately affect plant and soil community dynamics at the ecosystem scale \underline{and} maximizing the nutrient retention and trophic energy capture capabilities of any given landscape requires a set of necessary and sufficient, successionally derived, soil food webs.}

\clearpage

%slide21------------------------------------------------
\subsubsection{Next steps}
\begin{enumerate}
	\item Optical microscopy training for the assessment of soil food web typologies.
	\item Quantitative assessment soil biota for the major successional stages of the Mayan successionally developed agroecosystem.
	\item Correlate soil food web typologies to successional stages using literature-derived data and field sample data.
	\item Build a LANDIS-II model of the Mayan successionally developed agroecosystem.
\end{enumerate}






%slide-----------------------------------------

\subsection{The Questions}    
\begin{itemize}
\item How can we design low-impact, low-input, robust, sustainable food production systems at the landscape scale that simultaneously maximize regional agricultural and ecological productivity?
\item Why do some agro-ecological practices work and some don't?
\item What are the causal links between landscape disturbance regimes, assemblages of soil biota, soil food webs, nutrient cycling processes, and landscape successional patterns? 
\item What are the agro-ecological landscape patterns that are necessary and sufficient for the processes of agricultural-ecological mutualism? Can these patterns be generated by \enquote*{tuning} landscape scale disturbance regimes?
\item Are ratios of bacteria:fungi:protozoa:nematodes:microarthropods (readily obtainable from optical microscopy using simple morphological typologies) necessary and sufficient state variables to assess the degree of agricultural-ecological mutualism for different agro-ecological landscape patterns?
\end{itemize}
